 36â†’ * The syntax is specified at
 37â†’ * <https://unicode-org.github.io/icu/userguide/format_parse/datetime/#datetime-format-syntax>.
 38â†’ *
 39â†’ * Currently, locale-aware directives are not supported, due to no locale support in Kotlin.
 40â†’ *
 41â†’ * In addition to the standard syntax, this function also supports the following extensions:
 42â†’ * * `[]` denote optional sections. For example, `hh:mm[:ss]` will allow parsing seconds optionally.
 43â†’ *   This is similar to what is supported by the Java Time's `DateTimeFormatter` class.
 44â†’ *
 45â†’ * Usage example:
 46â†’ * ```
 47â†’ * DateTimeComponents.Format {
 48â†’ *   // 2023-01-20T23:53:16.312+03:30[Asia/Tehran]
 49â†’ *   byUnicodePattern("uuuu-MM-dd'T'HH:mm[:ss[.SSS]]xxxxx'['VV']'")
